[src:calculus-of-variations/calculus-of-variations] Calculus of variations is concerned with variations of functionals, which are small changes in the functional's value due to small changes in the function that is its argument.
[src:calculus-of-variations/calculus-of-variations] The **first variation** is defined as the linear part of the change in the functional, and the **second variation** is defined as the quadratic part.
[src:calculus-of-variations/calculus-of-variations] Using the above definitions, especially the definitions of first variation, second variation, and strongly positive, the following sufficient condition for a minimum of a functional can be stated.
[src:calculus-of-variations/euler-lagrange-equation] In the calculus of variations and classical mechanics, the **Euler–Lagrange equations** are a system of second-order ordinary differential equations whose solutions are stationary points of the given action functional.
[src:calculus-of-variations/euler-lagrange-equation] The equations were discovered in the 1750s by Swiss mathematician Leonhard Euler and Italian mathematician Joseph-Louis Lagrange.
[src:calculus-of-variations/euler-lagrange-equation] Because a differentiable functional is stationary at its local extrema, the Euler–Lagrange equation is useful for solving optimization problems in which, given some functional, one seeks the function minimizing or maximizing it.
[src:calculus-of-variations/euler-lagrange-equation] This is analogous to Fermat's theorem in calculus, stating that at any point where a differentiable function attains a local extremum its derivative is zero.
[src:calculus-of-variations/euler-lagrange-equation] In Lagrangian mechanics, according to Hamilton's principle of stationary action, the evolution of a physical system is described by the solutions to the Euler equation for the action of the system.
[src:calculus-of-variations/euler-lagrange-equation] In this context Euler equations are usually called **Lagrange equations**.
[src:calculus-of-variations/euler-lagrange-equation] In classical mechanics, it is equivalent to Newton's laws of motion; indeed, the Euler–Lagrange equations will produce the same equations as Newton's Laws.
[src:calculus-of-variations/euler-lagrange-equation] This is particularly useful when analyzing systems whose force vectors are particularly complicated.
[src:calculus-of-variations/euler-lagrange-equation] It has the advantage that it takes the same form in any system of generalized coordinates, and it is better suited to generalizations.
[src:calculus-of-variations/euler-lagrange-equation] In classical field theory there is an analogous equation to calculate the dynamics of a field.
[src:calculus-of-variations/euler-lagrange-equation] The Euler–Lagrange equation was developed in the 1750s by Euler and Lagrange in connection with their studies of the tautochrone problem.
[src:calculus-of-variations/euler-lagrange-equation] This is the problem of determining a curve on which a weighted particle will fall to a fixed point in a fixed amount of time, independent of the starting point.
[src:calculus-of-variations/euler-lagrange-equation] Lagrange solved this problem in 1755 and sent the solution to Euler.
[src:calculus-of-variations/euler-lagrange-equation] Both further developed Lagrange's method and applied it to mechanics, which led to the formulation of Lagrangian mechanics.
[src:calculus-of-variations/euler-lagrange-equation] Their correspondence ultimately led to the calculus of variations, a term coined by Euler himself in 1766.
[src:calculus-of-variations/euler-lagrange-equation] Let $(X,L)$ be a real dynamical system with n degrees of freedom.
[src:calculus-of-variations/euler-lagrange-equation] (For those familiar with differential geometry, X is a smooth manifold, and $L\colon {\mathbb {R} }_{t}\times TX\to {\mathbb {R} },$ where $TX$ is the tangent bundle of X ).
[src:calculus-of-variations/euler-lagrange-equation] When we say stationary point, we mean a stationary point of S with respect to any small perturbation in ${\boldsymbol {q}}$ .
