[src:calculus-of-variations/functional-mathematics] In mathematics, a **functional** is a certain type of function.
[src:calculus-of-variations/functional-mathematics] The exact definition of the term varies depending on the subfield (and sometimes even the author).
[src:calculus-of-variations/functional-mathematics] This article is mainly concerned with the second concept, which arose in the early 18th century as part of the calculus of variations.
[src:calculus-of-variations/functional-mathematics] The first concept, which is more modern and abstract, is discussed in detail in a separate article, under the name linear form.
[src:calculus-of-variations/functional-mathematics] The third concept is detailed in the computer science article on higher-order functions.
[src:calculus-of-variations/functional-mathematics] In the case where the space X is a space of functions, the functional is a "function of a function", and some older authors actually define the term "functional" to mean "function of a function".
[src:calculus-of-variations/functional-mathematics] However, the fact that X is a space of functions is not mathematically essential, so this older definition is no longer prevalent.
[src:calculus-of-variations/functional-mathematics] The term originates from the calculus of variations, where one searches for a function that minimizes (or maximizes) a given functional.
[src:calculus-of-variations/functional-mathematics] A particularly important application in physics is search for a state of a system that minimizes (or maximizes) the action, or in other words the time integral of the Lagrangian.
[src:calculus-of-variations/functional-mathematics] The mapping $x_{0}\mapsto f(x_{0})$ is a function, where $x_{0}$ is an argument of a function $f.$ At the same time, the mapping of a function to the value of the function at a point $f\mapsto f(x_{0})$ is a *functional*; here, $x_{0}$ is a parameter.
[src:calculus-of-variations/functional-mathematics] Provided that f is a linear function from a vector space to the underlying scalar field, the above linear maps are dual to each other, and in functional analysis both are called linear functionals.
[src:calculus-of-variations/functional-mathematics] Integrals such as $f\mapsto I[f]=\int _{\Omega }H(f(x),f'(x),\ldots )\;\mu (\mathrm {d} x)$ form a special class of functionals.
[src:calculus-of-variations/functional-mathematics] They map a function f into a real number, provided that H is real-valued.
[src:calculus-of-variations/functional-mathematics] If a functional's value can be computed for small segments of the input curve and then summed to find the total value, the functional is called local.
[src:calculus-of-variations/functional-mathematics] This occurs commonly when integrals occur separately in the numerator and denominator of an equation such as in calculations of center of mass.
[src:calculus-of-variations/functional-mathematics] The traditional usage also applies when one talks about a functional equation, meaning an equation between functionals: an equation $F=G$ between functionals can be read as an 'equation to solve', with solutions being themselves functions.
[src:calculus-of-variations/functional-mathematics] Functional derivatives are used in Lagrangian mechanics.
[src:calculus-of-variations/functional-mathematics] They are derivatives of functionals; that is, they carry information on how a functional changes when the input function changes by a small amount.
[src:calculus-of-variations/functional-mathematics] Richard Feynman used functional integrals as the central idea in his sum over the histories formulation of quantum mechanics.
[src:calculus-of-variations/functional-mathematics] This usage implies an integral taken over some function space.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] In mathematics, the **isoperimetric inequality** is a geometric inequality involving the square of the circumference of a closed curve in the plane and the area of a plane region it encloses, as well as its various generalizations.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] *Isoperimetric* literally means "having the same perimeter".
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] and that equality holds if and only if the curve is a circle.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] The **isoperimetric problem** is to determine a plane figure of the largest possible area whose boundary has a specified length.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] The closely related *Dido's problem* asks for a region of the maximal area bounded by a straight line and a curvilinear arc whose endpoints belong to that line.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] It is named after Dido, the legendary founder and first queen of Carthage.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] The solution to the isoperimetric problem is given by a circle and was known already in Ancient Greece.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] However, the first mathematically rigorous proof of this fact was obtained only in the 19th century.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] Since then, many other proofs have been found.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] The isoperimetric problem has been extended in multiple ways, for example, to curves on surfaces and to regions in higher-dimensional spaces.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] Perhaps the most familiar physical manifestation of the 3-dimensional isoperimetric inequality is the shape of a drop of water.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] Namely, a drop will typically assume a symmetric round shape.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] Since the amount of water in a drop is fixed, surface tension forces the drop into a shape which minimizes the surface area of the drop, namely a round sphere.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] The classical *isoperimetric problem* dates back to antiquity.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] The problem can be stated as follows: Among all closed curves in the plane of fixed perimeter, which curve (if any) maximizes the area of its enclosed region?
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] This question can be shown to be equivalent to the following problem: Among all closed curves in the plane enclosing a fixed area, which curve (if any) minimizes the perimeter?
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] This problem is conceptually related to the principle of least action in physics, in that it can be restated: what is the principle of action which encloses the greatest area, with the greatest economy of effort?
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] The 15th-century philosopher and scientist, Cardinal Nicholas of Cusa, considered rotational action, the process by which a circle is generated, to be the most direct reflection, in the realm of sensory impressions, of the process by which the universe is created.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] German astronomer and astrologer Johannes Kepler invoked the isoperimetric principle in discussing the morphology of the Solar System, in *Mysterium Cosmographicum* (*The Sacred Mystery of the Cosmos*, 1596).
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] Although the circle appears to be an obvious solution to the problem, proving this fact is rather difficult.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] The first progress toward the solution was made by Swiss geometer Jakob Steiner in 1838, using a geometric method later named *Steiner symmetrisation*.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] Steiner showed that if a solution existed, then it must be the circle.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] Steiner's proof was completed later by several other mathematicians.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] Steiner begins with some geometric constructions which are easily understood; for example, it can be shown that any closed curve enclosing a region that is not fully convex can be modified to enclose more area, by "flipping" the concave areas so that they become convex.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] It can further be shown that any closed curve which is not fully symmetrical can be "tilted" so that it encloses more area.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] The one shape that is perfectly convex and symmetrical is the circle, although this, in itself, does not represent a rigorous proof of the isoperimetric theorem (see external links).
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] The solution to the isoperimetric problem is usually expressed in the form of an inequality that relates the length *L* of a closed curve and the area *A* of the planar region that it encloses.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] and that the equality holds if and only if the curve is a circle.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] The area of a disk of radius *R* is *πR*2 and the circumference of the circle is 2*πR*, so both sides of the inequality are equal to 4*π*2*R*2 in this case.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] Dozens of proofs of the isoperimetric inequality have been found.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] In 1902, Hurwitz published a short proof using the Fourier series that applies to arbitrary rectifiable curves (not assumed to be smooth).
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] An elegant direct proof based on comparison of a smooth simple closed curve with an appropriate circle was given by E.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] It uses only the arc length formula, expression for the area of a plane region from Green's theorem, and the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] For a given closed curve, the **isoperimetric quotient** is defined as the ratio of its area and that of the circle having the same perimeter.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] and the isoperimetric inequality says that *Q* ≤ 1.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] Equivalently, the isoperimetric ratio *L*2/*A* is at least 4π for every curve.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] Let C be a smooth regular convex closed curve.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] where $L,A,{\widetilde {A}}_{0.5}$ denote the length of C , the area of the region bounded by C and the oriented area of the Wigner caustic of C , respectively, and the equality holds if and only if C is a curve of constant width.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] Let *C* be a simple closed curve on a sphere of radius 1.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] Denote by *L* the length of *C* and by *A* the area enclosed by *C*.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] There are, in fact, two ways to measure the spherical area enclosed by a simple closed curve, but the inequality is symmetric with the respect to taking the complement.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] This inequality was discovered by Paul Lévy (1919) who also extended it to higher dimensions and general surfaces.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] The isoperimetric inequality states that a sphere has the smallest surface area per given volume.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] where $B_{1}\subset \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is a unit ball.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] The equality holds when S is a ball in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] Under additional restrictions on the set (such as convexity, regularity, smooth boundary), the equality holds for a ball only.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] But in full generality the situation is more complicated.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] The relevant result of Schmidt (1949, Sect.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] 20.7) (for a simpler proof see Baebler (1957)) is clarified in Hadwiger (1957, Sect.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] An extremal set consists of a ball and a "corona" that contributes neither to the volume nor to the surface area.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] That is, the equality holds for a compact set S if and only if S contains a closed ball B such that $\operatorname {vol} (B)=\operatorname {vol} (S)$ and $\operatorname {per} (B)=\operatorname {per} (S).$ For example, the "corona" may be a curve.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] The proof of the inequality follows directly from Brunn–Minkowski inequality between a set S and a ball with radius $\epsilon$ , i.e. $B_{\epsilon }=\epsilon B_{1}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] where $M_{*}^{n-1}$ is the (*n*-1)-dimensional Minkowski content, *Ln* is the *n*-dimensional Lebesgue measure, and *ωn* is the volume of the unit ball in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] If the boundary of *S* is rectifiable, then the Minkowski content is the (*n*-1)-dimensional Hausdorff measure.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] Hadamard manifolds are complete simply connected manifolds with nonpositive curvature.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] Thus they generalize the Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , which is a Hadamard manifold with curvature zero.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] holds for bounded sets S in Hadamard manifolds, which has become known as the Cartan–Hadamard conjecture.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] In dimension 2 this had already been established in 1926 by André Weil, who was a student of Hadamard at the time.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] In dimensions 3 and 4 the conjecture was proved by Bruce Kleiner in 1992, and Chris Croke in 1984 respectively.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] Most of the work on isoperimetric problem has been done in the context of smooth regions in Euclidean spaces, or more generally, in Riemannian manifolds.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] However, the isoperimetric problem can be formulated in much greater generality, using the notion of *Minkowski content*.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] Let $(X,\mu ,d)$ be a *metric measure space*: *X* is a metric space with metric *d*, and *μ* is a Borel measure on *X*.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] The isoperimetric problem in *X* asks how small can $\mu ^{+}(A)$ be for a given *μ*(*A*).
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] If *X* is the Euclidean plane with the usual distance and the Lebesgue measure then this question generalizes the classical isoperimetric problem to planar regions whose boundary is not necessarily smooth, although the answer turns out to be the same.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] is called the *isoperimetric profile* of the metric measure space $(X,\mu ,d)$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] Isoperimetric profiles have been studied for Cayley graphs of discrete groups and for special classes of Riemannian manifolds (where usually only regions *A* with regular boundary are considered).
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] In graph theory, isoperimetric inequalities are at the heart of the study of expander graphs, which are sparse graphs that have strong connectivity properties.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] Expander constructions have spawned research in pure and applied mathematics, with several applications to complexity theory, design of robust computer networks, and the theory of error-correcting codes.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] Isoperimetric inequalities for graphs relate the size of vertex subsets to the size of their boundary, which is usually measured by the number of edges leaving the subset (edge expansion) or by the number of neighbouring vertices (vertex expansion).
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] For a graph G and a number k , the following are two standard isoperimetric parameters for graphs.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] Here $E(S,{\overline {S}})$ denotes the set of edges leaving S and $\Gamma (S)$ denotes the set of vertices that have a neighbour in S .
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] The isoperimetric problem consists of understanding how the parameters $\Phi _{E}$ and $\Phi _{V}$ behave for natural families of graphs.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] The d -dimensional hypercube $Q_{d}$ is the graph whose vertices are all Boolean vectors of length d , that is, the set $\{0,1\}^{d}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] Two such vectors are connected by an edge in $Q_{d}$ if they are equal up to a single bit flip, that is, their Hamming distance is exactly one.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] The following are the isoperimetric inequalities for the Boolean hypercube.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] The edge isoperimetric inequality of the hypercube is $\Phi _{E}(Q_{d},k)\geq k(d-\log _{2}k)$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] This bound is tight, as is witnessed by each set S that is the set of vertices of any subcube of $Q_{d}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] Harper's theorem says that *Hamming balls* have the smallest vertex boundary among all sets of a given size.
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] Hamming balls are sets that contain all points of Hamming weight at most r and no points of Hamming weight larger than $r+1$ for some integer r .
[src:calculus-of-variations/isoperimetric-inequality] with equality for the equilateral triangle.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] Noether's theorem is used in theoretical physics and the calculus of variations.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] It reveals the fundamental relation between the symmetries of a physical system and the conservation laws.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] It also made modern theoretical physicists much more focused on symmetries of physical systems.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] A generalization of the formulations on constants of motion in Lagrangian and Hamiltonian mechanics (developed in 1788 and 1833, respectively), it does not apply to systems that cannot be modeled with a Lagrangian alone (e.g., systems with a Rayleigh dissipation function).
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] In particular, dissipative systems with continuous symmetries need not have a corresponding conservation law.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] The physical system itself need not be symmetric; a jagged asteroid tumbling in space conserves angular momentum despite its asymmetry.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] It is the laws of its motion that are symmetric.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] Noether's theorem is important, both because of the insight it gives into conservation laws, and also as a practical calculational tool.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] It allows investigators to determine the conserved quantities (invariants) from the observed symmetries of a physical system.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] Conversely, it allows researchers to consider whole classes of hypothetical Lagrangians with given invariants, to describe a physical system.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] As an illustration, suppose that a physical theory is proposed which conserves a quantity *X*.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] A researcher can calculate the types of Lagrangians that conserve *X* through a continuous symmetry.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] Due to Noether's theorem, the properties of these Lagrangians provide further criteria to understand the implications and judge the fitness of the new theory.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] There are numerous versions of Noether's theorem, with varying degrees of generality.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] There are natural quantum counterparts of this theorem, expressed in the Ward–Takahashi identities.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] Generalizations of Noether's theorem to superspaces also exist.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] The word "symmetry" in the above statement refers more precisely to the covariance of the form that a physical law takes with respect to a one-dimensional Lie group of transformations satisfying certain technical criteria.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] The conservation law of a physical quantity is usually expressed as a continuity equation.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] The formal proof of the theorem utilizes the condition of invariance to derive an expression for a current associated with a conserved physical quantity.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] In modern terminology, the conserved quantity is called the *Noether charge*, while the flow carrying that charge is called the *Noether current*.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] The Noether current is defined up to a solenoidal (divergenceless) vector field.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] The main idea behind Noether's theorem is most easily illustrated by a system with one coordinate q and a continuous symmetry $\varphi :q\mapsto q+\delta q$ (gray arrows on the diagram).
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] Consider any trajectory $q(t)$ (bold on the diagram) that satisfies the system's laws of motion.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] That is, the action S governing this system is stationary on this trajectory, i.e. does not change under any local variation of the trajectory.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] In particular it would not change under a variation that applies the symmetry flow $\varphi$ on a time segment [*t*0, *t*1] and is motionless outside that segment.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] To keep the trajectory continuous, we use "buffering" periods of small time $\tau$ to transition between the segments gradually.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] The total change in the action S now comprises changes brought by every interval in play.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] Parts where variation itself vanishes, i.e. outside $[t_{0},t_{1}]$ , bring no $\Delta S$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] The middle part does not change the action either, because its transformation $\varphi$ is a symmetry and thus preserves the Lagrangian L and the action ${\textstyle S=\int L}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] The only remaining parts are the "buffering" pieces.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] So the regions contribute mostly through their "slanting" ${\dot {q}}\rightarrow {\dot {q}}\pm \delta q/\tau$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] These last terms, evaluated around the endpoints $t_{0}$ and $t_{1}$ , should cancel each other in order to make the total change in the action $\Delta S$ be zero, as would be expected if the trajectory is a solution.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] That is $\left({\frac {\partial L}{\partial {\dot {q}}}}\varphi \right)(t_{0})=\left({\frac {\partial L}{\partial {\dot {q}}}}\varphi \right)(t_{1}),$ meaning the quantity $\left(\partial L/\partial {\dot {q}}\right)\varphi$ is conserved, which is the conclusion of Noether's theorem.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] For instance if pure translations of q by a constant are the symmetry, then the conserved quantity becomes just $\left(\partial L/\partial {\dot {q}}\right)=p$ , the canonical momentum.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] A conservation law states that some quantity *X* in the mathematical description of a system's evolution remains constant throughout its motion – it is an invariant.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] Such quantities are said to be conserved; they are often called constants of motion (although motion *per se* need not be involved, just evolution in time).
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] For example, if the energy of a system is conserved, its energy is invariant at all times, which imposes a constraint on the system's motion and may help in solving for it.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] Aside from insights that such constants of motion give into the nature of a system, they are a useful calculational tool; for example, an approximate solution can be corrected by finding the nearest state that satisfies the suitable conservation laws.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] The earliest constants of motion discovered were momentum and kinetic energy, which were proposed in the 17th century by René Descartes and Gottfried Leibniz on the basis of collision experiments, and refined by subsequent researchers.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] Isaac Newton was the first to enunciate the conservation of momentum in its modern form, and showed that it was a consequence of Newton's laws of motion.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] The local conservation of non-gravitational linear momentum and energy in a free-falling reference frame is expressed by the vanishing of the covariant divergence of the stress–energy tensor.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] Another important conserved quantity, discovered in studies of the celestial mechanics of astronomical bodies, is the Laplace–Runge–Lenz vector.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] In the late 18th and early 19th centuries, physicists developed more systematic methods for discovering invariants.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] A major advance came in 1788 with the development of Lagrangian mechanics, which is related to the principle of least action.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] In this approach, the state of the system can be described by any type of generalized coordinates **q**; the laws of motion need not be expressed in a Cartesian coordinate system, as was customary in Newtonian mechanics.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] Hamilton's principle states that the physical path **q**(*t*)—the one actually taken by the system—is a path for which infinitesimal variations in that path cause no change in *I*, at least up to first order.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] is conserved throughout the motion (on the physical path).
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] Thus, the absence of the **ignorable** coordinate *qk* from the Lagrangian implies that the Lagrangian is unaffected by changes or transformations of *qk*; the Lagrangian is invariant, and is said to exhibit a symmetry under such transformations.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] This is the seed idea generalized in Noether's theorem.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] Several alternative methods for finding conserved quantities were developed in the 19th century, especially by William Rowan Hamilton.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] For example, he developed a theory of canonical transformations which allowed changing coordinates so that some coordinates disappeared from the Lagrangian, as above, resulting in conserved canonical momenta.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] Another approach, and perhaps the most efficient for finding conserved quantities, is the Hamilton–Jacobi equation.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] Emmy Noether's work on the invariance theorem began in 1915 when she was helping Felix Klein and David Hilbert with their work related to Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity By March 1918 she had most of the key ideas for the paper which would be published later in the year.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] The essence of Noether's theorem is generalizing the notion of ignorable coordinates.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] One can assume that the Lagrangian *L* defined above is invariant under small perturbations (warpings) of the time variable *t* and the generalized coordinates **q**.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] where the perturbations *δt* and *δ***q** are both small, but variable.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] For generality, assume there are (say) *N* such symmetry transformations of the action, i.e. transformations leaving the action unchanged; labelled by an index *r* = 1, 2, 3, ..., *N*.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] For translations, **Q***r* is a constant with units of length; for rotations, it is an expression linear in the components of **q**, and the parameters make up an angle.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] For illustration, consider a Lagrangian that does not depend on time, i.e., that is invariant (symmetric) under changes *t* → *t* + δ*t*, without any change in the coordinates **q**.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] Consider a Lagrangian which does not depend on an ("ignorable", as above) coordinate *q**k*; so it is invariant (symmetric) under changes *q**k* → *q**k* + *δq**k*.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] In special and general relativity, these two conservation laws can be expressed either *globally* (as it is done above), or *locally* as a continuity equation.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] The global versions can be united into a single global conservation law: the conservation of the energy-momentum 4-vector.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] The local versions of energy and momentum conservation (at any point in space-time) can also be united, into the conservation of a quantity defined *locally* at the space-time point: the stress–energy tensor(this will be derived in the next section).
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] The conservation of the angular momentum **L** = **r** × **p** is analogous to its linear momentum counterpart.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] It is assumed that the symmetry of the Lagrangian is rotational, i.e., that the Lagrangian does not depend on the absolute orientation of the physical system in space.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] Since time is not being transformed, *T* = 0, and *N* = 1.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] In other words, the component of the angular momentum **L** along the **n** axis is conserved.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] And if **n** is arbitrary, i.e., if the system is insensitive to any rotation, then every component of **L** is conserved; in short, angular momentum is conserved.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] Although useful in its own right, the version of Noether's theorem given above is a special case of the general version derived in 1915.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] To give the flavor of the general theorem, a version of Noether's theorem for continuous fields in four-dimensional space–time is now given.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] Since field theory problems are more common in modern physics than mechanics problems, this field theory version is the most commonly used version of Noether's theorem.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] Let there be a set of differentiable fields $\varphi$ defined over all space and time; for example, the temperature $T(\mathbf {x} ,t)$ would be representative of such a field, being a number defined at every place and time.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] (the theorem can be further generalized to the case where the Lagrangian depends on up to the *n*th derivative, and can also be formulated using jet bundles).
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] where $\Psi$ is in general a function that may depend on both $x^{\mu }$ and $\varphi$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] The condition for $\Psi$ to generate a physical symmetry is that the action ${\mathcal {S}}$ is left invariant.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] since the integral of a divergence becomes a boundary term according to the divergence theorem.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] (where the dot product is understood to contract the *field* indices, not the $\nu$ index or r index).
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] which expresses the idea that the amount of a conserved quantity within a sphere cannot change unless some of it flows out of the sphere.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] For example, electric charge is conserved; the amount of charge within a sphere cannot change unless charge enters or leaves the sphere.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] For illustration, consider a physical system of fields that behaves the same under translations in time and space, as considered above; in other words, $L\left({\boldsymbol {\varphi }},\partial _{\mu }{\boldsymbol {\varphi }},x^{\mu }\right)$ is constant in its third argument.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] In that case, *N* = 4, one for each dimension of space and time.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] and thus Noether's theorem corresponds to the conservation law for the stress–energy tensor *T**μ**ν*, where we have used $\mu$ in place of r .
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] (we relabelled $\mu$ as $\sigma$ at an intermediate step to avoid conflict).
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] The conservation of electric charge, by contrast, can be derived by considering *Ψ* linear in the fields *φ* rather than in the derivatives.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] In quantum mechanics, the probability amplitude *ψ*(**x**) of finding a particle at a point **x** is a complex field *φ*, because it ascribes a complex number to every point in space and time.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] The probability amplitude itself is physically unmeasurable; only the probability *p* = |*ψ*|2 can be inferred from a set of measurements.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] In the limit when the phase *θ* becomes infinitesimally small, *δθ*, it may be taken as the parameter *ε*, while the *Ψ* are equal to *iψ* and −*iψ**, respectively.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] which, when multiplied by the charge on that species of particle, equals the electric current density due to that type of particle.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p01] This "gauge invariance" was first noted by Hermann Weyl, and is one of the prototype gauge symmetries of physics.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] Consider the simplest case, a system with one independent variable, time.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] is invariant under brief infinitesimal variations in the dependent variables.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] And suppose that the integral is invariant under a continuous symmetry.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] where *ε* is a real variable indicating the amount of flow, and *T* is a real constant (which could be zero) indicating how much the flow shifts time.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] which may be regarded as a function of *ε*.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] is a constant of the motion, i.e., it is a conserved quantity.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] To avoid excessive complication of the formulas, this derivation assumed that the flow does not change as time passes.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] The same result can be obtained in the more general case.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] where ${\textstyle {\cal {P}}}$ is a closed path in ${\textstyle {\cal {D}}}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] Here, the *function* ${\textstyle S(\mathbf {q} ,t)}$ is the action *function* that is computed by the integration of the Lagrangian over optimal trajectories or equivalently obtained through the Hamilton-Jacobi equation.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] As ${\textstyle \partial S/\partial \mathbf {q} =\mathbf {p} }$ (where ${\textstyle \mathbf {p} }$ is the momentum) and ${\textstyle \partial S/\partial t=-H}$ (where ${\textstyle H}$ is the Hamiltonian), the differential of this function is given by ${\textstyle dS=\mathbf {p} d\mathbf {q} -Hdt}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] Using the geometrical approach, the conserved quantity for a symmetry in Noether's sense can be derived.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] The closed path ${\textstyle {\cal {P}}}$ of integration is chosen as ${\textstyle ABB'A'}$ , where the branches ${\textstyle AB}$ and ${\textstyle A'B'}$ are given ${\textstyle {\cal {C}}}$ and ${\textstyle {\cal {C}}'}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] Therefore, to the first order in ${\textstyle \epsilon }$ , the quantity $I=\mathbf {p} \phi _{\mathbf {q} }-H\phi _{t}$ is conserved along the trajectory.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] Noether's theorem may also be derived for tensor fields $\varphi ^{A}$ where the index *A* ranges over the various components of the various tensor fields.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] These field quantities are functions defined over a four-dimensional space whose points are labeled by coordinates *x*μ where the index *μ* ranges over time (*μ* = 0) and three spatial dimensions (*μ* = 1, 2, 3).
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] These four coordinates are the independent variables; and the values of the fields at each event are the dependent variables.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] By this definition, the field variations $\delta \varphi ^{A}$ result from two factors: intrinsic changes in the field themselves and changes in coordinates, since the transformed field *α**A* depends on the transformed coordinates ξμ.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] If the coordinates are changed, the boundary of the region of space–time over which the Lagrangian is being integrated also changes; the original boundary and its transformed version are denoted as Ω and Ω', respectively.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] Noether's theorem begins with the assumption that a specific transformation of the coordinates and field variables does not change the action, which is defined as the integral of the Lagrangian density over the given region of spacetime.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] where the comma subscript indicates a partial derivative with respect to the coordinate(s) that follows the comma, e.g.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] where ${\mathcal {L}}_{X}\varphi ^{A}$ is the Lie derivative of $\varphi ^{A}$ in the *X**μ* direction.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] Suppose we have an *n*-dimensional oriented Riemannian or more generally Lorentzian manifold, *M* and a target manifold *T*.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] Let ${\mathcal {C}}$ be the configuration space of smooth functions from *M* to *T*.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] To get to the usual version of Noether's theorem, we need additional restrictions on the action.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] called the Lagrangian density, depending on $\varphi$ , its derivative and the position.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] Suppose we are given boundary conditions, i.e., a specification of the value of $\varphi$ at the boundary if *M* is compact, or some limit on $\varphi$ as *x* approaches ∞.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] and that $\varphi$ satisfies the given boundary conditions, is the subspace of on shell solutions.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] If this holds on shell and off shell, we say *Q* generates an off-shell symmetry.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] If this only holds on shell, we say *Q* generates an on-shell symmetry.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] If the symmetry generated by *Q* integrates to a continuous symmetry, we say that *Q* is the generator of a one parameter symmetry Lie group.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] which is called the **Noether current** associated with the symmetry.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] The continuity equation tells us that if we integrate this current over a space-like slice, we get a conserved quantity called the Noether charge (provided, of course, if *M* is noncompact, the currents fall off sufficiently fast at infinity).
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] Noether's theorem is an on shell theorem: it relies on the use of the equations of motion—the classical path.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] It reflects the relation between the boundary conditions and the variational principle.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] The quantum analogs of Noether's theorem involving expectation values (e.g., ${\textstyle \left\langle \int \partial \cdot {\textbf {J}}~d^{4}x\right\rangle =0}$ ) probing off shell quantities as well are the Ward–Takahashi identities.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] Suppose we have two symmetry derivations *Q*1 and *Q*2.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] Then, [*Q*1, *Q*2] is also a symmetry derivation.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] This shows we can extend Noether's theorem to larger Lie algebras in a natural way.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] This applies to *any* local symmetry derivation *Q* satisfying *QS* ≈ 0, and also to more general local functional differentiable actions, including ones where the Lagrangian depends on higher derivatives of the fields.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] Let *ε* be any arbitrary smooth function of the spacetime (or time) manifold such that the closure of its support is disjoint from the boundary.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] This is the generalization of Noether's theorem.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] To see how the generalization is related to the version given above, assume that the action is the spacetime integral of a Lagrangian that only depends on $\varphi$ and its first derivatives.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] Looking at the specific case of a Newtonian particle of mass *m*, coordinate *x*, moving under the influence of a potential *V*, coordinatized by time *t*.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] The first term in the brackets is the kinetic energy of the particle, while the second is its potential energy.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] Consider the generator of time translations $Q={\frac {d}{dt}}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] The right hand side is the energy, and Noether's theorem states that $dj/dt=0$ (i.e. the principle of conservation of energy is a consequence of invariance under time translations).
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] for N Newtonian particles where the potential only depends pairwise upon the relative displacement.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] For ${\vec {Q}}$ , consider the generator of Galilean transformations (i.e. a change in the frame of reference).
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] where ${\vec {P}}$ is the total momentum, *M* is the total mass and ${\vec {x}}_{CM}$ is the center of mass.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] Both examples 1 and 2 are over a 1-dimensional manifold (time).
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] An example involving spacetime is a conformal transformation of a massless real scalar field with a quartic potential in (3 + 1)-Minkowski spacetime.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] For *Q*, consider the generator of a spacetime rescaling.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] The second term on the right hand side is due to the "conformal weight" of $\varphi$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] Noether's theorem states that $\partial _{\mu }j^{\mu }=0$ (as one may explicitly check by substituting the Euler–Lagrange equations into the left hand side).
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] If one tries to find the Ward–Takahashi analog of this equation, one runs into a problem because of anomalies.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] Application of Noether's theorem allows physicists to gain insights into any general theory in physics, by just analyzing the various transformations that would make the form of the laws involved invariant.
[src:calculus-of-variations/noether-s-theorem-p02] The Noether charge is also used in calculating the entropy of stationary black holes.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Several distinct action principles differ in the constraints on their initial and final conditions.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The names of action principles have evolved over time and differ in details of the endpoints of the paths and the nature of the variation.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Quantum action principles generalize and justify the older classical principles by showing they are a direct result of quantum interference patterns.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Action principles are the basis for Feynman's version of quantum mechanics, general relativity and quantum field theory.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The action principles have applications as broad as physics, including many problems in classical mechanics but especially in modern problems of quantum mechanics and general relativity.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] These applications increased and expanded over two centuries as the power of the method and its further mathematical development rose.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] This article introduces the action principle concepts and summarizes other articles with more details on concepts and specific principles.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Action principles are "integral" approaches rather than the "differential" approach of Newtonian mechanics.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The core ideas are based on energy, paths, an energy function called the Lagrangian along paths, and selection of a path according to the "action", a continuous sum or integral of the Lagrangian along the path.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Introductory study of mechanics, the science of interacting objects, typically begins with Newton's laws based on the concept of force, defined by the acceleration it causes when applied to mass: *F* = *ma*.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] This approach to mechanics focuses on a single point in space and time, attempting to answer the question: "What happens next?".
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Mechanics based on action principles begin with the concept of action, an energy tradeoff between kinetic energy and potential energy, defined by the physics of the problem.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] These approaches answer questions relating starting and ending points: Which trajectory will place a basketball in the hoop?
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] If we launch a rocket to the Moon today, how can it land there in 5 days?
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The Newtonian and action-principle forms are equivalent, and either one can solve the same problems, but selecting the appropriate form will make solutions much easier.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The energy function in the action principles is not the total energy (conserved in an isolated system), but the Lagrangian, the difference between kinetic and potential energy.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The kinetic energy combines the energy of motion for all the objects in the system; the potential energy depends upon the instantaneous position of the objects and drives the motion of the objects.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The motion of the objects places them in new positions with new potential energy values, giving a new value for the Lagrangian.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Using energy rather than force gives immediate advantages as a basis for mechanics.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Force mechanics involves three-dimensional vector calculus, with three space and three momentum coordinates for each object in the scenario; energy is a scalar magnitude combining information from all objects, giving an immediate simplification in many cases.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The components of force vary with coordinate systems; the energy value is the same in all coordinate systems.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Force requires an inertial frame of reference; once velocities approach the speed of light, special relativity profoundly affects mechanics based on forces.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] In action principles, relativity merely requires a different Lagrangian: the principle itself is independent of coordinate systems.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The explanatory diagrams in force-based mechanics usually focus on a single point, like the center of momentum, and show vectors of forces and velocities.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The explanatory diagrams of action-based mechanics have two points with actual and possible paths connecting them.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] These diagrammatic conventions reiterate the different strong points of each method.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Depending on the action principle, the two points connected by paths in a diagram may represent two particle positions at different times, or the two points may represent values in a configuration space or in a phase space.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The mathematical technology and terminology of action principles can be learned by thinking in terms of physical space, then applied in the more powerful and general abstract spaces.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Action principles assign a number—the action—to each possible path between two points.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] where the form of the kinetic energy (KE) and potential energy (PE) expressions depend upon the physics problem, and their value at each point on the path depends upon relative coordinates corresponding to that point.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The energy function is called a Lagrangian; in simple problems it is the kinetic energy minus the potential energy of the system.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] In classical mechanics, a system moving between two points takes one particular path; other similar paths are not taken.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Each conceivable path corresponds to a value of the action.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] An action principle predicts or explains that the particular path taken has a stationary value for the system's action: similar paths near the one taken have very similar action value.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] This variation in the action value is key to the action principles.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] In quantum mechanics, every possible path contributes an amplitude to the system's behavior, with the phase of each amplitude determined by the action for that path (phase = ⁠action/ħ⁠).
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] When the scale of the problem is much larger than the Planck constant ħ (the classical limit), only the stationary action path survives the interference.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] meaning that at the stationary point, the variation of the action S with some fixed constraints C is zero.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] For action principles, the stationary point may be a minimum or a saddle point, but not a maximum.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Elliptical planetary orbits provide a simple example of two paths with equal action – one in each direction around the orbit; neither can be the minimum or "least action".
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The path variation implied by δ is not the same as a differential like dt.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The action integral depends on the coordinates of the objects, and these coordinates depend upon the path taken.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Thus the action integral is a functional, a function of a function.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] An important result from geometry known as Noether's theorem states that any conserved quantities in a Lagrangian imply a continuous symmetry and conversely.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] For examples, a Lagrangian independent of time corresponds to a system with conserved energy; spatial translation independence implies momentum conservation; angular rotation invariance implies angular momentum conservation.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] These examples are global symmetries, where the independence is itself independent of space or time; more general *local* symmetries having a functional dependence on space or time lead to gauge theory.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The observed conservation of isospin was used by Yang Chen-Ning and Robert Mills in 1953 to construct a gauge theory for mesons, leading some decades later to modern particle physics theory.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Action principles apply to a wide variety of physical problems, including all of fundamental physics.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The only major exceptions are cases involving friction or when only the initial position and velocities are given.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Different action principles have different meaning for the variations; each specific application of an action principle requires a specific Lagrangian describing the physics.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] A common name for any or all of these principles is "the principle of least action".
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] For a discussion of the names and historical origin of these principles see action principle names.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] When total energy and the endpoints are fixed, Maupertuis's least action principle applies.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] For example, to score points in basketball the ball must leave the shooters hand and go through the hoop, but the time of the flight is not constrained.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Some textbooks write (*δW*)*E* = 0 as Δ*S*0, to emphasize that the variation used in this form of the action principle differs from Hamilton's variation.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Here the total energy E is fixed during the variation, but not the time, the reverse of the constraints on Hamilton's principle.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Consequently, the same path and end points take different times and energies in the two forms.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The solutions in the case of this form of Maupertuis's principle are orbits: functions relating coordinates to each other in which time is simply an index or a parameter.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] For time-invariant system, the action S relates simply to the abbreviated action W on the stationary path as $\Delta S=\Delta W-E\Delta t$ for energy E and time difference Δ*t* = *t*2 − *t*1.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] When the physics problem gives the two endpoints as a position and a time, that is as events, Hamilton's action principle applies.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] For example, imagine planning a trip to the Moon.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] During your voyage the Moon will continue its orbit around the Earth: it is a moving target.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The Lagrangian $L=T-V$ is the difference between kinetic energy and potential energy at each point on the path.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Solution of the resulting equations gives the world line **q**(*t*).
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Starting with Hamilton's principle, the local differential Euler–Lagrange equation can be derived for systems of fixed energy.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The action S in Hamilton's principle is the Legendre transformation of the action in Maupertuis's principle.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The concepts and many of the methods useful for particle mechanics also apply to continuous fields.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The action integral runs over a Lagrangian density, but the concepts are so close that the density is often simply called the Lagrangian.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] For quantum mechanics, the action principles have significant advantages: only one mechanical postulate is needed, if a covariant Lagrangian is used in the action, the result is relativistically correct, and they transition clearly to classical equivalents.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Both Richard Feynman and Julian Schwinger developed quantum action principles based on early work by Paul Dirac.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Feynman's integral method was not a variational principle but reduces to the classical least action principle; it led to his Feynman diagrams.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Schwinger's differential approach relates infinitesimal amplitude changes to infinitesimal action changes.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] When quantum effects are important, new action principles are needed.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Instead of a single path with stationary action, all possible paths add (the integral over *xk*), weighted by a complex probability amplitude *e**iS*⁄*ħ*.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The phase of the amplitude is given by the action divided by the Planck constant or quantum of action: ⁠*S*/*ħ*⁠.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] When the action of a particle is much larger than ħ, ⁠*S*/*ħ*⁠ ≫ 1, the phase changes rapidly along the path: the amplitude averages to a small number.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Thus the Planck constant sets the boundary between classical and quantum mechanics.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] All of the paths contribute in the quantum action principle.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] At the end point, where the paths meet, the paths with similar phases add, and those with phases differing by π subtract.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Close to the path expected from classical physics, phases tend to align; the tendency is stronger for more massive objects that have larger values of action.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] In the classical limit, one path dominates – the path of stationary action.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The Schwinger form makes analysis of variation of the Lagrangian itself, for example, variation in potential source strength, especially transparent.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] For every path, the action integral builds in value from zero at the starting point to its final value at the end.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Any nearby path has similar values at similar distances from the starting point.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Lines or surfaces of constant partial action value can be drawn across the paths, creating a wave-like view of the action.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Analysis like this connects particle-like rays of geometrical optics with the wavefronts of Huygens–Fresnel principle.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Action principles are applied to derive differential equations like the Euler–Lagrange equations or as direct applications to physical problems.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Action principles can be directly applied to many problems in classical mechanics, such as the shape of elastic rods under load, the shape of a liquid between two vertical plates (a capillary), or the motion of a pendulum when its support is in motion.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Quantum action principles are used in the quantum theory of atoms in molecules (QTAIM), a way of decomposing the computed electron density of molecules in to atoms as a way of gaining insight into chemical bonding.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Inspired by Einstein's work on general relativity, the renowned mathematician David Hilbert applied the principle of least action to derive the field equations of general relativity.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] contained a relativistically invariant volume element √−*g* *d*4*x* and the Ricci scalar curvature R.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The scale factor $\kappa$ is the Einstein gravitational constant.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The action principle is so central in modern physics and mathematics that it is widely applied including in thermodynamics, fluid mechanics, the theory of relativity, quantum mechanics, particle physics, and string theory.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] The action principle is preceded by earlier ideas in optics.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] In ancient Greece, Euclid wrote in his *Catoptrica* that, for the path of light reflecting from a mirror, the angle of incidence equals the angle of reflection.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Hero of Alexandria later showed that this path has the shortest length and least time.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] In 1915, David Hilbert applied the variational principle to derive Albert Einstein's equations of general relativity.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] In 1933, the physicist Paul Dirac demonstrated how this principle can be used in quantum calculations by discerning the quantum mechanical underpinning of the principle in the quantum interference of amplitudes.
[src:calculus-of-variations/principle-of-least-action] Subsequently Julian Schwinger and Richard Feynman independently applied this principle in quantum electrodynamics.
